metadata.name: barcodes #27
metadata.description:
The title of my collection is ‚Äúbarcodes‚Äù, as unique visual identifiers for their respective generative token. 

Barcodes initially displayed data by varying width, spacing, and size of the lines. Today, we can additionally separate barcodes by color and hidden layers.

In our realm of little dots and noise, we can distinguish data (token holder, contract address, purchase history) using these features, but we can add one more:

The time it takes for the ‚Äúpitch to drop‚Äù. The pace of the barcode‚Äôs formation.

metadata.name: Brutal Infection #170
metadata.description:
Brutal Infection explores the concept of structural organisms from a dystopian vision.The use of muted colors reflects the cold and inhuman nature of the organisms, while also emphasizing the sense of evolution, emergence, and life within these structures.

The compositions are based on trigonometric functions, aligning geometric shapes into abstract forms, creating a sense of harmony and balance amidst the chaos and turmoil of the structural organisms.

The viewer is invited to examine the tiniest details, as they are the most interesting, alive, and emerging parts of the structures themselves.
___________________

Due to differences in how shaders operate in different engines, there may be slight differences between the preview image and the live-rendered output.

To obtain the live-rendered version, you can press the 's' key in live view or alternatively, you can right-click and save the preview image.

Made with p5js and glsl shaders.

Best experienced in fullscreen.

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: A Bugged Forest #80
metadata.description:
A forest has stories to tell.
About times that were, about times that will be.
-
This project was minted in much unusual conditions. 
We gathered here, by 38 degrees heat. We belong to a crowd who loves stories, of civilisations at stake and deities, of afterlife and worship. We drank and hugged and chanted pagan hymns. We minted the Bugged Forest from our place on earth that we call Hell just for the fun of it. We are passionate, and loving, and angry and desperate. We, people of the soil, under a bugged sun.
-
This project is the long-form version of an algorithm that contains a bug. ‚ÄúThe Bugged Tree‚Äù‚Äôs code was salvaged and stored and served as the core motivation and engine for an entire forest. Its concept is about releasing the control. I am a  byproduct of evolution, an iteration of that specie who wanted utter control, and which at some point, lost control over its own creation. As a generative artist, I chose to welcome the event of chance into my creative process. The symbolism in chance made me feel humble and free. Unwilling to make any change to a story that the Tree needed to tell me, as a listener, rather than a writer of my own idealised fantasies.
-
The iterations aren‚Äôt under control. They may be odd and off. We have to accept it. They are also plottable, press [s] in live mode to get a SVG. Attempt the plot at your own risk, as there‚Äôs a possibility for it to come near to impossibilities or cause paper or motor damage, and most certainly, a bugged drawing.
-
From Earth or from Hell, with love, yours truthfully, NFTBiker and zancan

metadata.name: Paper Mandala #137
metadata.description:
A collaboration with P1xelboy and Paper Buddha.
Beautiful paper mandalas made purely with code in Paper Buddha's style.
Features include:
27 different palettes
3 different mandala types (Lotus, Starburst Style 1 and Starburst Style 2)
Four sections of the mandala with one of 10 different pattern types (Dots, Checks, Crosses, Triangles, Stripes, Circles, Polygons, Lazers, Quadrants and Hatching)
4 different direction types of shadow - of varying length
Randomly placed star background
Randomly placed Nebula
Possible Special Pattern Effect with darker stippling pattern
Possible Nirvana Effect where random colors are added to one of either Golden, Silver, Bronze, Blue Moon or Sea Green palettes.

Using only code, this produces a unique output which does take a few seconds to load.
Press "S" to Save your unique Paper Mandala as a 2048 x 2048 JPG
Press "R" for a random shuffle effect - (please wait for reload) - Refresh page to reset

The project works in a responsive browser, so to set up for phone background or watch, resize the browser accordingly and Alt + Print Screen to get an appropriately sized image.

Offered as a Dutch Auction, holders of the first 20 tokens (1-20) will receive additional benefits in the form of utility for future releases in the P1xelboy/Paper Mandala collaboration series. (exact details to be determined)
This utility will remain attached to tokens 1-20 and transfer to the new owner upon subsequent secondary sales.

Uses p5.js and p5.pattern
@p1x3lboy @paperbuddha - September 2022

metadata.name: Minimalist #14
metadata.description:
This abstract art is produced by exercising concepts of minimalism. Each artwork is composed of simple figures and simple engaging colors. 

Each abstract art piece is generated to connect with a specific type of person. When the viewer sees an abstract image that resonates with him or her a connection is made. 

This artwork was produced using computer graphics software and randomly layerd images.
